docs.lead_paragraph: The strike is over. Musicians and management of the Cleveland Orchestra on Tuesday approved terms of a settlement over a wage dispute that had prompted a strike Monday. Salaries remain frozen this season and the next. They will go up by 3 percent in the first half of the 2011-12 season and by another 2 percent in the second half. The musicians have agreed to donate up to 10 rehearsals and concerts over the life of the contract. They will pay higher premiums for health insurance starting in July 2011. The agreement was announced by the musicians' committee chairman, Jeffrey Rathbun, and the orchestra's executive director, Gary Hanson.

docs.lead_paragraph: The consensus on the left is a resounding no. According to Jonathan Chait, Matt Yglesias, E.J. Dionne, and many others, Obama's political difficulties are explained by a lousy economy, rather than a public backlash against liberalism. Like Ronald Reagan, who suffered a similar first-term swoon, the president is a prisoner of circumstance: His program is suddenly unpopular not because it's too liberal and ambitious, but because the unemployment rate is around 10 percent and holding. In this climate, any agenda would be unpopular, and Obama would having exactly the same problems if he'd governed as a cautious incrementalist rather than a would-be Lyndon Johnson.
docs.abstract: Liberals say no. Here's why they might be wrong.

docs.lead_paragraph: In 2007, San Francisco began Healthy San Francisco (HSF), "a health access plan" (read: health services) for poor residents without insurance. Last winter, H.S.F. expanded to middle-class residents. Justine Sharrock, a writer who also happens to be the daughter of an anesthesiologist, signed up in 2009, when the upper limit on annual income was increased to $54,150 for a single person (and $110,250 for a family of four).
